        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We propose to use band 7 because (1) the flux (greater than ~ 1.7 Jy 
in 850Î¼m band) will be the highest and (2) the spatial resolution 
will be the highest among the available bands for polarization
 observation in Cycle 2. To resolve the features shown in Figure 1 
and to detect weak extended emission coming from circumstellar medium, 
we request 0.12" angular resolution with a desired sensitivity per 
pointing at 0.03 mJy. 

Line contamination in the continuum band 7:
IRC+10216 shows a very rich spectrum of molecular and atomic lines 
particularly at millimeter and submillimeter wavelengths (e.g., 
Groesbeck et al. 1994; Patel et al. 2011; Cernicharo et al. 2013). 
Patel et al (2011) made line survey observations in short mm/submm 
bands using the SMA. There are relatively strong lines such as SiC2, 
SiS, C34S C2H, and SiO lines in the base bands that we observe with 
ALMA. We can reconstruct the continuum from the line-free channels 
on the coase frequency resolution spectrum in TDM mode.
Based on the SMA measurements done by Patel et al. 2011, 
6.5GHz out of 8GHz might be usable as the line free channels.  
However, many of the line emission detected in line surveys may be 
resolved out by these high resolution ALMA observations. For this case, 
line contamination will be much less of a problem for this project. 
For the worst case, if we use only 6.5 GHz band as line free channels, 
it will result in about 1.11 times worse sensitivity comparing with 
the sensitivity estimated using the sensitivity calcurator. 

The continuum emission must come much more compact region comparing with the 
area inside the lowest contour of the HCN map in the left of Figure 1 
(roughly corresponds to 80 synthesized beams of area).   
When the expected flux of 1.7 Jy (for the minimum case) is distributed in 
roughly 50 synthesized beams, one beam receives 34 mJy. 

ALMA is the only instrument that allows us to image both compact (coming from 
the photosphere) and extended (inner circumstellar dust) components of  
polarization of the emission in high signal-to-noise ratio.
We expect to detect _at least_ 3 percent of linear polarization degree based 
on the polarized SiO emission shown in Figure 1 and 2. 
3 % of 34 mJy that one synthesized beam receives corresponds to ~1 mJy. 
When we consider the factor of line free channel (1.26 as explained above
for the worst case), 
the desired sensitivity wil become 1.1 mJy. 
This is roughly 37 times higher than the desired sensitivity per pointing 
estimated by the sensitivity calcurator.  

This observation is to be completed within 3 hours, which is the minimum 
required observing time for any polarization observations including 
calibration observations.
</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
